<TITLE> Gaziul Haque laid to rest </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 18 (bdnews24.com)Language movement hero Gaziul Haque, who died Wednesday aged 80, has been buried at the family graveyard of his Bogra home. He was laid to rest Thursday evening next to his father's grave, said family members. People from across the social spectrum thronged the Central Shaheed Minar premises earlier in the day paying their last respects to Gaziul. Cabinet members, educationists, politicians, teachers, students, writers, litterateurs and other professionals placed floral wreaths on the coffin. Two namaz-e-janaza were held for him in the morning at the Baitul Mokarram national mosque and the Supreme Court premises. Former caretaker government chief Habibur Rahman, incumbent finance minister AMA Muhith, information minister Abul Kalam Azad, AL leaders Amir Hossain Amu and Abdur Razzak, BNP secretary general Khandaker Delwar Hossain, BNP standing committee members Moudud Ahmed and MK Anwar, among others, attended the janaza. The Qulkhwani of the language veteran will be held on June 26 in Dhaka. Daughter Sujata Haque told bdnews24.com on Wednesday her father, who had suffered for long from a number of ailments, had fallen unconscious at home and was moved to hospital. Doctors at Square Hospital declared him dead. Haque was a vanguard of the 1952 Language Movement, and played major roles in all the democratic movements in the then East Pakistan through to the 1971 independence war. He championed socio-cultural causes through his life. Prime minister Sheikh Hasina heard the sad news while she was in parliament and rushed to the hospital to pay her respects to the hero. bdnews24.c
